#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:118
msgid ""
"See the documentation for the `convenience classes <routines.polynomials."
"classes>`_ for further details on the ``domain`` and ``window`` attributes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:122
msgid ""
"Another major difference between the legacy polynomial module and the "
"polynomial package is polynomial fitting. In the old module, fitting was "
"done via the `~numpy.polyfit` function. In the polynomial package, the "
"`~numpy.polynomial.polynomial.Polynomial.fit` class method is preferred. For "
"example, consider a simple linear fit to the following data:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:1
msgid ""
"In [1]: rng = np.random.default_rng()\n"
"\n"
"In [2]: x = np.arange(10)\n"
"\n"
"In [3]: y = np.arange(10) + rng.standard_normal(10)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:134
msgid ""
"With the legacy polynomial module, a linear fit (i.e. polynomial of degree "
"1) could be applied to these data with `~numpy.polyfit`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:1
msgid ""
"In [4]: np.polyfit(x, y, deg=1)\n"
"Out[4]: array([ 1.06100449, -0.54360836])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:141
msgid ""
"With the new polynomial API, the `~numpy.polynomial.polynomial.Polynomial."
"fit` class method is preferred:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:1
msgid ""
"In [5]: p_fitted = np.polynomial.Polynomial.fit(x, y, deg=1)\n"
"\n"
"In [6]: p_fitted\n"
"Out[6]: Polynomial([4.23091186, 4.77452022], domain=[0., 9.], window=[-1.,  "
"1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:149
msgid ""
"Note that the coefficients are given *in the scaled domain* defined by the "
"linear mapping between the ``window`` and ``domain``. `~numpy.polynomial."
"polynomial.Polynomial.convert` can be used to get the coefficients in the "
"unscaled data domain."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:1
msgid ""
"In [7]: p_fitted.convert()\n"
"Out[7]: Polynomial([-0.54360836,  1.06100449], domain=[-1.,  1.], "
"window=[-1.,  1.], symbol='x')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:159
msgid "Documentation for the `~numpy.polynomial` package"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/routines.polynomials.rst:161
msgid ""
"In addition to standard power series polynomials, the polynomial package "
"provides several additional kinds of polynomials including Chebyshev, "
"Hermite (two subtypes), Laguerre, and Legendre polynomials. Each of these "
"has an associated `convenience class <routines.polynomials.classes>` "
"available from the `numpy.polynomial` namespace that provides a consistent "
"interface for working with polynomials regardless of their type."
msgstr ""

